William Amamoo, the former Black Stars of Ghana goalkeeper has tipped his country to get past Nigeria for a place at this year’s FIFA World Cup taking place in Qatar, the United Arabs Emirates, in November. The former goalkeeper acknowledged the fierce rivalry that existed and still exists between Nigeria and Ghana, comparing it to that between Ghanaian clubs Asante Kotoko and Hearts of Oak, but said that his country would qualify ahead of Nigeria at the long last. Amamoo, now retired, said matches between the two West African giants does not follow form guide and is confident the Black Stars will edge past their Nigeria counterparts. “Matches between Ghana and Nigeria doesn’t follow form guide and because of that I have a strong believe that Ghana will beat Nigeria”, he told Accra-based radio station. “Ghana and Nigeria games are just like that of Hearts of Oak and Asante Kotoko, though Kotoko was in great form, they couldn’t beat struggling Hearts and that gives me the Believe that Ghana will win on 25th by all means” “Ghana must beat Nigeria heavily here in Ghana in the first leg to make the second in Nigeria a mere formality just as we did in 2014 against Egypt when we beat them 6-1 here before the second game in Cairo”, he added The Black Stars will battle it out with Nigeria for one of the slots to represent Africa at the World Cup tournament in November in a two-leg encounter. Ghana host Nigeria in the first leg on March 25, 2022, before playing away in the reverse fixture on March 29 at the Moshood Abiola Stadium in Abuja..